Programmatic corpus for javelin-steno; describes a type system and reusable function families too large to enumerate. Unlike dict.steno, this is never flattened into a stroke→text map. Instead, `build-javelin` renders two small lookup tables (types and constructs) into C++, and the runtime replays the append walk per keystroke.

Types are records with stroke, arity, and text with `%t` argument markers; nesting is unbounded — a generic's argument can itself be any type to any depth, unlike dict.steno's arity-0 pool restriction. Four base types are defined: `TPH` (number), `STR` (string), `PW` (boolean), `AR` (Array<%t>, arity 1), `PH` (Map<%t,%t>, arity 2).

The "STKWR-T" construct is a type emitter that appends any type to any depth; `TKPW-T/AR/AR/AR/TPH` expands to Array<Array<Array<number>>>. This shallow-enumerable construct is the pin for walker-vs-pipeline differential tests.

The "STKWR-PBGS/-L" construct emits a function with 0–15 parameters via the AOEU count bank. `@fuse` merges the return type `%T` into the shape stroke (fused return slot stroked first, then each parameter slot in template order), generating 16 construct records instead of T^16 rows. The format adds `%T` (D11, fuse-target type slot) to docs/steno-format.md vocabulary; see docs/pipeline.md "The reference walker."